DP  - 1978
TI  - [Genetic factors in the etiology of breast cancer (author's transl)].
PG  - 127-30
AB  - A review of literature shows that, at present, genetic factors are difficult to 
      distinguish from environmental factors. A number of studies have put into light 
      relationships between factors tranmetted genetically and an increased risk of 
      breast cancer in some women. This might be a reflect of the transmission of a 
      certain susceptibility. However, one of these factors alone cannot explain the 
      increase of the risk. Most likely, as for many types of cancers, the development 
      of breast cancer is due both to a multigenic transmission of a certain 
      susceptibility and to the action of environmental factors. Though, 
      epidemiological studies make possible to identify a high risk population. A 
      regular follow-up of this population would permit early diagnosis and possibly 
      prophylactic measures concerning the known environmental factors, and in 
      particular hormonal factors.
