DP  - 1978 May
TI  - Estrogen profiles in young women: effect of maternal history of breast cancer.
PG  - 965-7
AB  - To examine the hypothesis that familial breast cancer risk is related to estrogen 
      metabolism, we analyzed urines of daughters of breast cancer patients and their 
      matched controls for estrone (E1), estradiol (E2), and estriol (E3). From this, 
      we computed estriol proportions (E3/E1 + E2 + E3). "Patient-daughters" and the 
      matched controls showed no differences in estriol proportions. Our results failed 
      to support the hypothesis that high-risk women (those with a family history of 
      breast cancer) have relatively lower estriol proportions, and we concluded that 
      whatever family history contributes to breast cancer risk, that risk is not 
      likely to be transmitted by the estrogen profile.
