OAB - A study designed to test the hypothesis that daughters of breast cancer patients 
      would have "less favorable" estriol proportions than would a group of otherwise 
      similar controls is reported. Urinary estrogen profiles of 46 daughters born to 
      45 women who later developed breast cancer and of 46 controls were examined. 
      Computed estriol proportions (estriol/estrone plus estradiol plus estriol) 
      revealed no differences in "patient-daughters" and the matched controls. It is 
      concluded that whatever family history contributes to breast cancer risk, that 
      risk is not likely transmitted by the estrogen profile.
